        "answer_count": 3,
        "title": "Argument checking or Design-by-Contract in java (GWT). Where to start?",
        "body": "<p>I am playing GWT. I am looking for basic argument checking. I do not require invariants or result ensures. \nWhat I am interested about it best practises on the topic.<\/p>\n\n<p>For example, in c# I use one of this options:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><code>if (arg1 != null) throw new ArgumentNulException....; //  Official for public API;<\/code><\/li>\n<li><code>Args.NotNull(arg1); // Home grown.<\/code><\/li>\n<li><code>Contracts.Requires(arg1 != null); // Internal contract validation.<\/code><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>What is the best place for me to start?<\/p>\n\n<p>Ok, what I found for now.<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.javapractices.com/topic/TopicAction.do?Id=5\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Validate method arguments<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://java.sun.com/j2se/1.4.2/docs/guide/lang/assert.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Programming With Assertions<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n",
        "question_id": 868291,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "design-by-contract"
        ],
        "score": 1,
        "accepted_answer_id": 868466,
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 687,
        "last_edit_date": 1253396471
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ced11826cb92c2e759c45bef134ca534?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 15083,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 31506,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/31506/jack-leow",
                "reputation": 22557,
                "display_name": "Jack Leow"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1242391360,
            "creation_date": 1242391360,
            "body": "<p>I typically just do it myself, per the recommendations of <a href=\"https://rads.stackoverflow.com/amzn/click/com/0321356683\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Effective Java<\/a> by Josh Bloch, so:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>if (arg == null) throw new NullPointerException(\"arg cannot be null\");\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>or<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>if (arg &lt; 0) throw new IllegalArgumentException(\"arg must be positive\");\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>I'd highly recommend getting a copy of <a href=\"https://rads.stackoverflow.com/amzn/click/com/0321356683\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Effective Java<\/a> if you don't already have it.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 868466,
            "question_id": 868291
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7e4805742d316ceeda4ee98502107cbd?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 26299,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 68296,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/68296/stefan-sveidqvist",
                "reputation": 3514,
                "display_name": "Stefan Sveidqvist",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1242631540,
            "creation_date": 1242389514,
            "body": "<p>According to the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Design_by_contract\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">wikipedia page of Design by Contract<\/a>, popular tools for this methodology with Java are:<\/p>\n\n<p>iContract2, Contract4J, jContractor, Jcontract, C4J, CodePro Analytix, STclass, Jass preprocessor, OVal with AspectJ, Java Modeling Language (JML), SpringContracts for the Spring framework, or Modern Jass, Custos using AspectJ,JavaDbC using AspectJ, JavaTESK using extension of Java.<\/p>\n\n<p>Reading up on one of those is probably a good idea.<\/p>\n\n<p>I have no personal experience of any of them but Pragmatic Programmer says good things about the original iContract so that might be a good place to start.<\/p>\n\n<p>You could always try doing it on your own by using Javas built-in assertions:<\/p>\n\n<p><code>\nassert Expression1;\n<\/code><br>\nor<br>\n<code>\nassert Expression1 : Expression2 ;\n<\/code><\/p>\n\n<p>Where Expression1 results in a boolean and Expression2 is the value your testing (optional). Try it out.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 868320,
            "question_id": 868291,
            "last_edit_date": 1242631540
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6910d674f8ae12e1a84183e7400cf2d2?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 55764,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 167077,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/167077/christian-lemer",
                "reputation": 893,
                "display_name": "Christian Lemer",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1253396393,
            "creation_date": 1253396393,
            "body": "<p>If you are just looking for arguments checking, then a simple check with exception should be the best solution.<\/p>\n\n<p>Exception provides you a better solution for catching an processing than simple assertions.<\/p>\n\n<p>In that scenario Design-by-Contract solutions are definitively overkill.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 1449610,
            "question_id": 868291
        }
    ],
